                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d75">
                <head>75. Memorandum to the File<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d75fn1">Source:
                        Department of State, Files of the Deputy Secretary of State—Deputy Secretary
                            <persName corresp="#p_DKW_1">Kenneth Dam</persName> Official Files,
                        1982–1985, Lot 85D308, Personal Notes of Deputy Secretary—<persName
                            corresp="#p_DKW_1">Kenneth W. Dam</persName>—Oct. 1984–June 1985. No
                        classification marking. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_DKW_1"
                            >Dam</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1984-10-24">October 24, 1984</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I sat in on the Secretary’s meeting with Assistant Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_AE_1">Abrams</persName>, who is in charge of the Human Rights
                    Bureau of the Department. We discussed a variety of topics, particularly the
                    question of Soviet Jewry. The Secretary expressed his view that if we were to
                    establish a better working relationship with the Soviet Union, the chances are
                    that the Soviets would be willing to see more Jews emigrate from the Soviet
                    Union. He said that at one point <persName corresp="#p_GDP_2">Gromyko</persName>
                    had as much as told him so. But he thought that in any event it was likely to be
                    so because the <pb facs="0272" n="226" xml:id="pg_226"/> Soviets seemed to be
                    using the rate of emigration as a policy tool to bring leverage on the United
                    States. In the meantime, we should continue to express our views to the Soviets
                    on all human rights issues on every possible occasion.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here are discussions not related to human rights.]</p>
            </div>
        </body>
